		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> LOTR Q&A Rulings from 04/08/04<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=617'>Enrique "Max of Tat" Huerta</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=617&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 22, 2004</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Not for review.<br />
Originally posted 04/08/04.<br />
===========================<br />
<br />
<br />
Hello All!!<br />
<br />
  I&#39;m very sorry for missing out on last week&#39;s update. Work sent me out of town for the week and I was unable to connect to the internet. I would complain, but they sent me to England, first class. So as you can see, I&#39;m doing the best I can with the cards I&#39;ve been dealt. (= And this postponement works out nicely since I&#39;m being sent to Orlando next week and I would have had trouble with that update anyway. (=<br />
<br />
  As a result, this is one of my biggest updated ever! I hope you enjoy. See you in two weeks! <br />
<br />
- Enrique<br />
<br />
<br />
<h3>Questions about Card Rulings:</h3><br />
<b>Hey,<br />
i got a question about the new sting.<br />
<br />
When u play a 15 strenght minion for example that is fierce and in the fierce he his a strenght 7 frodo with the sting. What happens? Does he get discarded with one threat and frodo overwelmed anyhow?Does Frodo survive? Thnx. [Mas3rTech]</b><br />
<br />
Frodo would be overwhelmed because the total strength of the Shadow side is double (or greater) then his strength. When Frodo is overwhelmmed, he&#39;s placed in the Dead Pile and all cards on him are placed in the discard pile. You would not be able to use Sting, Bane of Eight Legs.<br />
<br />
The reason you can not use Sting in this situation is because Sting (and Frodo) must survive until the &quot;end of the skirmish&quot;. The &quot;end of the skirmish&quot; does not occur until AFTER all actions triggered by winning/losing the skirmish occur. After all those actions, the skirmish is &quot;about to end&quot; and that is when you can use Sting&#39;s response action.<br />
<br />
<b>Hi, this might seem a stoopid question but here goes : <br />
U assign a E Captain To frodo , u have one burden. He has a polearm and 2 wounds cse of archery. <br />
If you play paths what happens? <br />
<br />
U pay the cost and the wound just doesn&#39;t triger? [Mas3rTech]</b><br />
<br />
<b>OK, here&#39;s the scenario: One burden on Frodo, an exhausted Easterling Captain in play with Easterling Polearm. The Captain is assigned to Frodo, and the FP&#39;s player plays, Power According To His Stature, wounding the captain. But as soon as he adds a burden, does the polearm&#39;s text kick in and prevent the wound, or does it kill him? Thanks. [Quickbeam]</b><br />
<br />
You must pay the cost of the action before you get any of the effects. Once the Free Peoples player adds the burden for the cost, the game text of the Easterling Polearm will trigger. This occurs before the effect of wounding the minion and since it&#39;s before the wounding, it protects the Easterling Captain from the wound.<br />
<br />
<b>I have a question about the term: being put into the dead pile. Does it counts as killed too. <br />
<br />
In an example, if I play Saved From the Fire on Theoden, Tall and Proud, can I fetch a Rohan character as well as three Rohan cards? Thanks in advance. [Ringbearer]</b><br />
<br />
Yes, placing Theoden in your dead pile with Saved From the Fire counts as being &quot;killed&quot;.<br />
<br />
You would not &quot;fetch&quot; another ROhan companion like you are fetching three cards from that culture. The difference being that you must play the companion immediately. The other cards go to your hand and do not have to be played immediately. I&#39;m guessing you knew that already, but I wanted to clarify.<br />
<br />
<b>I was play testing a wraith with gandalf guidance (just a name) last night and I came upon two cards Saved from the Fire/ Elessar&#39;s Edict can I do that as a combo Saved.. says &quot;Spot Gandalf and place a companion (except Ring Bearer) in dead pile to take 3 cards from that companions culture into hand from draw deck. Elessar&#39;s Edict is a response that says, &quot; If a (Gondor) Wraith is about to be killed, discard him and exhaust another (Gondor) wraith instead. Can I play this combo legally or since I am placing the wraith in my dead pile. If legal is there any cards that would allow me to get the discarded wraith from discard. Thank you much. [jedikilla]</b><br />
<br />
The cost of Saved from the Fire is to place a companion in the dead pile. This has been ruled to be the same as &quot;killing&quot; a companion. You may play Elessar&#39;s Edict to prevent the Wraith from going to the discard pile and prevent them from being killed. However, if you do so, you&#39;re also preventing the cost of Saved from the Fire. Unless you pay the costs, you do not get the effects. So yes, the cards can be played legally, but you will not get the effects of Saved from the Fire if you also play Elessar&#39;s Edict.<br />
<br />
Gandalf, Greyhame allows you to play characters from your discard pile.<br />
<br />
<b>Simple. Can you throw away a zero cost card with Grond and how? And with Bold men and grim if frodo is about to die can the shadow player discard Sam first before he takes the ring ? [George Karabinis] </b><br />
<br />
1. You would remove 0 tokens (X=0) and either discard a [Saruon] minion or Grond. Remember, 0 is a legal number in LOTR.<br />
<br />
2. Yes, Bold Men and Grim triggers before a companion is killed. Sam&#39;s response special ability workd after Frodo dies. So Bold Men and Grim can discard Sam before Frodo is about to die.<br />
<br />
<b>Hello Enrique I got a question on the new errata on Elessar&#39;s Edict. It is the grammatical context that I want clarified. The card states that when a Gondor wraith is about to be killed, there are two different options you can do with the response. It is the second response i wish to be clarified. If a gondor wraith is about to be killed, can you play Elessar&#39;s Edict and spot another Gondor wraith to prevent that wraith from being killed? [wet&juicy]</b><br />
<br />
Elessar&#39;s Edict has been clarified in the lastest CRD:<br />
<i>§ Elessar¹s Edict    8 R 33<br />
If a (Gondor) Wraith is about to be killed, discard him and either exhaust another (Gondor) Wraith or spot another exhausted (Gondor) Wraith to prevent that.</i><br />
<br />
You can spot another Gondor wraith to prevent the first Wraith from being killed, as long as the wraith you spot is exhausted.<br />
<br />
<b>On Terrible and Evil, can I exert Gandalf 3 times and place wounds on 2 minions instead of one ? [Bobcat64]</b><br />
<br />
No. Terrible and Evil only lets you wound a single minion. If it used the term &quot;for each&quot; then you&#39;d be able to wound a minion for each exertion.<br />
<br />
<h3>Questions about Game/Tournament Rulings:</h3><br />
<b>hey there. this is my first time writing. i play a beserker deck. and came across a situation that needs clearing up. i have devilry of orthanc with 5 tokens on it. and beserk slayer is out (cost 7) with a broad bladed sword, his skirmish text states remove 5 tokens from a machine and exert slayer twice to wound every companion. no he has 7 companions out. 4 are exhausted and he has 4 threats. when everyone gets wounded 2 more become exhausted. now, do all the people that get wounded from the slayer die at the same time? and then the threats are done, killing 2 more guys potentially? or do they die one at a time, giving the free peeps a chance to get rid of the threats and killing off someone that would die otherwise?  [witchking 1]</b><br />
<br />
The effect of the action is to wound each companion once. Each wounding is done one at a time and in the order of the Free Peoples Player&#39;s choosing (mandatory actions). If the FPP wishes to first wound a companion that is exhausted, thereby setting off the 4 threats, they may apply those threats to other exhausted companions that would die from Devilry of Orthanc anyway. This is a savy tactic to help reduce the effects of threat wounds against a fellowship.<br />
<br />
As a tip, you might also consider this tactic for skirmishes that you know you&#39;re going to lose. Let Thrarin die to Ulaire Cantea and apply threat wounds to the companion skirmishing the Twilight Witch-king. If that companion dies because of the threat wounds, the Twilight Witch-king does NOT win his skirmish, so your Ring-bearer is safe for at least one more skirmish. (The same would work against Dunlendings and War Clubs.)<br />
<br />
<b>Hi! <br />
<br />
First, congrats for you great work. And second my question about Brought back alive. ¿Could the Shadow Player assign a minion with Brought Back Alive to an alredy assigned companion? <br />
<br />
Thanks a lot! [BlackCat]</b><br />
<br />
First off, thank you. (=<br />
<br />
Secondly... No, you may not assign a minion with Brought Back Alive to an already assigned companion. All assignment actions must involve characters that are currently unassigned and may only result in one-on-one skirmishes. If the companion is already assigned, they are not a legal &quot;target&quot; for Brought Back Alive.<br />
<br />
Please note that Defender +X characters and the assigning of leftover minions do not fall under this restriction.<br />
<br />
<b>5 stars - good article but what happnes if a exausted mithrandir moves from city gate, are the three threats removed and then mithrandir dies or does mithrandir die and the 3 threats activate? d-mail me plz. (+3 tp) [Imrahil] </b><br />
<br />
There are 3 parts of a move.<br />
1. Moving &quot;from&quot; a site.<br />
2. Moving or &quot;moves&quot;.<br />
3. Moving &quot;to&quot; a site.<br />
<br />
Actions that trigger during the move trigger during one of those three parts of the move, in that order. City Gate says &quot;When the fellowship moves FROM this site...&quot;. So it would occur before Gandalf, Mithandir&#39;s game text which says &quot;Each time the fellowship MOVES...&quot;.<br />
<br />
Gandalf would still die, but after you&#39;ve removed the threats.<br />
<br />
<b>Hey Enrique, I came across this situation in an old tournament report. I&#39;ve seen rulings that if, for example, a player forgets to remove 3 threats when moving from City Gates, the ruling is that even though this is a mandatory action, the threats will remain if the mistake is noted later. Now, that being said, what if a player forgets to move his adventure marker down the site path? When a player says &quot;I move,&quot; moving that marker is another mandatory action, isn&#39;t it? This implies to me that if a player forgets to move their token, they can&#39;t later - and as such would be stuck at the same site. But that&#39;s a huge freakin&#39; setback for such a little mistake - what&#39;s the official ruling here? [Jason]</b><br />
<br />
A tricky situation to be sure, but a move token is merely a marker to show were the fellowship is for the purposes of game play. I wouldn&#39;t force a player to &quot;remain back&quot; at a site just because the move token wasn&#39;t moved. I also wouldn&#39;t allow a player to &quot;advance ahead&quot; a site if the moved their token from Site 4 straight to site 6.<br />
<br />
<b>It&#39;s simple really, but I want to ask anyways. If I, the Free Peoples, plays a card to reveal my own hand during my Fellowship phase and I have an Eye Of Barad-Dur in my hand, can I use the Eys&#39;s second ability to place burdens on my Frodo? I kinda figured you can&#39;t since all shadow cards are inactive during your Fellowship phase, but the Eye&#39;s text states &quot;Response: If a Free Peoples player reveals this card from your hand, discard this card to add 2 burdens.&quot; What do you think? [Zelfer] </b><br />
<br />
Your Shadow cards are not active during your turn. So eventhough Eye of Barad-Dur says &quot;if the Free Peoples player reveals this card...&quot; you can not play the card. It&#39;s the same reason you can not play Wizard&#39;s Staff on Saruman.<br />
<br />
<b>Hello Enrique, I have some questions concerning the new Theoden, Tall and Proud: 1) When Theoden is killed, can I play a Rohan companion (according to his text) before placing threat wounds? I believe I can&#39;t, because playing that companion is an optional action, while threat wounds are a required action but... well, your answer would be much appreciated :-) 2) Theoden is killed by the Witch-king carrying his Pale Blade... can I play Rohirrim Army from my deck and discard the W-K before he can use his Blade to discard my conditions? I would say I can, because they&#39;re both optional actions and I, as the FP player, can choose which one to solve first. Thank you for your time! [Valandil]</b><br />
<br />
You are correct on the first question. Threats are a mandatory action and they resolved before optional actions.<br />
<br />
You are mostly correct on the second one, but the effect is still basically the same. The reason the Rohirrim Army can discard the Witch-king first is because the Rohirrim Army comes into play as a result of THeoden being killed. It is all a part of the resolution of the mandatory actions from the Witch-king winning the skirmish. Discarding the Witck-king resolves the Rohirrim Army coming into play, which is a response to Theoden being killed, which is a response to the wounds (or being overwhelmed), which is a response to the Witch-king winning the skirmish. Once all that is resolved we&#39;d move on to optional actions which included The Pale Blade&#39;s gametext.<br />
<br />
Optional actions are not resolved according to the FPP preference. They are resolved in accordance for the action procedure [Comprehensive Rulebook, pg 13].<br />
<br />
<h3>Star Wars:CCG Rulings</h3><br />
<br />
<br />
- Enrique<br />
